WEBVTT

00:12.083 --> 00:15.709
Okay. So, before we get
to the questions,

00:15.792 --> 00:19.834
would you and the governor
like to answer
what I was saying about...

00:20.458 --> 00:22.667
I was quoting Norm Ornstein
and Thomas Mann.

00:22.750 --> 00:25.667
They're very, very esteemed
journalists.

00:25.750 --> 00:27.583
They were bipartisan.

00:28.083 --> 00:30.041
And they said it's
the Republicans' fault.

00:31.333 --> 00:35.417
I think that when
President Trump has
a good proposal,

00:35.792 --> 00:38.500
the country would be better off
if Democrats got behind it.

00:38.583 --> 00:40.208
-BILL: Like which one?
-Case in point--

00:40.291 --> 00:43.750
-(LAUGHTER)
-Case in point, how long do you
want to stay in Afghanistan?

00:43.834 --> 00:45.875
BILL: You're right.
That's the one I'm hoping for.

00:45.959 --> 00:50.542
And that-- And I know one
of the issues also is that
there is a deficit,

00:50.625 --> 00:55.375
and if you bring the troops back
from these regime-change wars,

00:55.667 --> 00:58.583
that you would save billions
of dollars and lives.

00:58.667 --> 01:00.166
-BILL: Yeah.
-And I think that's something

01:00.250 --> 01:01.458
that should have
bipartisan support.

01:01.542 --> 01:03.125
But the Republicans voted
against him on that!

01:03.208 --> 01:05.291
They finally found something
to stand up to him about,

01:05.375 --> 01:07.583
and it was, "You're not
for war enough."

01:07.667 --> 01:10.709
But, Bill, there is
an opportunity

01:10.792 --> 01:13.208
for a core of Democrats
and a core of Republicans

01:13.291 --> 01:16.792
to say, "You know what?
The president's got a good point
here, let's get behind him."

01:17.458 --> 01:20.125
Okay. Well, I'm for that.
I mean, you're right.

01:20.208 --> 01:23.417
The liberals have been
hypocritical about that.

01:23.625 --> 01:27.000
They were for ending
forever war, and now
they're for it.

01:27.083 --> 01:30.792
And when he talked about
family medical leave,
Chuck Schumer stood up,

01:30.875 --> 01:33.417
I think he was the only one
on the Democrat side who did it,
but then--

01:33.500 --> 01:35.667
You know, there, again,
reward good behavior.

01:35.750 --> 01:37.709
The first step at--

01:37.792 --> 01:42.458
To his credit, Cory Booker
brought somebody who had been
released from jail,

01:42.542 --> 01:47.333
who had been sentenced for
a long period of time,
and that...

01:47.583 --> 01:51.083
Criminal justice reform
and the FIRST STEP Act
passed in December.

01:51.166 --> 01:53.917
-BILL: Right.
-Great bipartisanship,
and it should be done again.

01:54.000 --> 01:56.667
Attacking opioids again,

01:57.333 --> 02:01.583
great national problem,
60,000 people a year
die from it,

02:01.667 --> 02:05.500
Democrats and Republicans have
a good opportunity to get behind
something like that when--

02:05.583 --> 02:08.834
And then, when he talks about
wiping out childhood leukemia,

02:08.917 --> 02:15.083
why not erupt with claps
and applause, saying,
"Hell yeah, let's do this"?

02:15.166 --> 02:16.542
Because this is
a horrible tragedy.

02:16.625 --> 02:19.000
Yeah, I don't think that
the Democrats are for
childhood leukemia.

02:19.083 --> 02:20.667
-(LAUGHTER)
-If that's what
you're implying.

02:20.750 --> 02:22.166
-I'm saying that--
-BILL: Okay. All right.

02:22.250 --> 02:24.583
-Building on the opportunity.
-So-- All right, you got
your rebuttal in.

02:24.667 --> 02:27.250
Governor Christie, do you think
there are any Democrats

02:27.333 --> 02:31.125
that have your signature
in-your-face approach
to dealing with the opposition?

02:31.208 --> 02:33.834
Is there a Democrat
Chris Christie?
I guess they're asking.

02:33.917 --> 02:35.959
-Well, thank God, no.
-(BILL LAUGHS)

02:36.041 --> 02:39.083
I-- No, listen, I think
Bernie has a bit of that.

02:39.375 --> 02:41.792
-BILL: Yeah. No, you're right.
-You know, Bernie doesn't
back down to anybody,

02:41.875 --> 02:44.250
and when Bernie's got a point
of view, he's gonna say it,

02:44.333 --> 02:46.625
and he doesn't really
sugarcoat anything,

02:46.709 --> 02:48.500
so I think Sanders is one
of those people.

02:48.583 --> 02:51.166
Who do you think is
the Democrats' best choice
to run in 2020?

02:51.250 --> 02:53.625
I think the one that
the president would be
most afraid of,

02:53.709 --> 02:56.709
if he can stay in his lane,
is Biden,

02:57.000 --> 03:01.125
and the reason why is because
Biden can go to Ohio,
and Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin,

03:01.208 --> 03:04.166
and Michigan, and appeal
to white working class voters.

03:04.792 --> 03:06.750
-And if he does that...
-(SCATTERED APPLAUSE)

03:06.834 --> 03:10.375
...he only has to peel off
seven to ten thousand votes

03:10.458 --> 03:12.166
in each one of those states
to be able--

03:12.250 --> 03:13.792
And he's just gotta win
two of them.

03:13.875 --> 03:16.834
But there's many states,
and he's not going to
excite the base anywhere.

03:16.917 --> 03:19.333
Yeah, but Biden-- I see, but--
Well, he's not gonna excite
the base, and--

03:19.417 --> 03:22.125
But you know what? That base
gets a little bit too excited,

03:22.375 --> 03:25.083
it's gonna drive away the rest
of the middle of the country,

03:25.166 --> 03:27.834
because some of the stuff
that the base is talking about

03:27.917 --> 03:31.208
is not gonna be appealing to
the middle of the country,

03:31.291 --> 03:33.709
and this is the same mistake
I think Democrats have made

03:33.792 --> 03:35.000
in a number
of different elections,

03:35.083 --> 03:36.792
where they say, "This is great,
we love it,"

03:36.875 --> 03:39.166
but they don't care
about what the middle
of the country thinks,

03:39.250 --> 03:40.542
they care about the two coasts.

03:40.625 --> 03:43.792
I'd also put in Tulsi Gabbard
and I'd put in John Delaney.

03:43.875 --> 03:48.041
If they get traction--
John Delaney has an incredible
business record,

03:48.125 --> 03:51.291
and Tulsi Gabbard, I think
she has a refreshing voice

03:51.375 --> 03:54.208
when it comes to these wars
that are endless
and regime change.

03:54.291 --> 03:56.834
-BILL: She's the one
the Russians like.
-CHRIS: What? (CHUCKLES)

03:56.917 --> 03:59.875
-But that investiga--
-BILL: I'm just saying,
the Russians like her.

03:59.959 --> 04:03.041
The New York Times
looked at that story
that NBC ran...

04:03.125 --> 04:05.542
-BILL: Right.
-...and discredited the guy
who claims it,

04:05.625 --> 04:08.125
this guy named Jonathan Morgan
and a group called--

04:08.208 --> 04:12.250
Okay. Eric Idle, as president
of the Footlights Club
at Cambridge,

04:12.333 --> 04:15.834
you were the first to allow
women to join. You, personally?

04:16.542 --> 04:17.917
-I did that, yes.
-BILL: You did!

04:18.000 --> 04:19.750
-Yes, I did do that.
-BILL: What motivated
your decision?

04:19.834 --> 04:20.917
